2 Installation
**************

2.1 System requirements
=======================

GGADT should install easily on most _Unix-based systems_ (e.g. Linux,
Mac) by following the standard GNU install procedures, described in
`INSTALL'.

     ./configure [--enable-openmp] ...
     make
     make install

2.2 Package dependencies
========================

   * *FFTW 3*. Available at `http://www.fftw.org/'.
        - _Further requirements for installing `ggadt-openmp'_: you
          must have the `fftw3_omp' libraries installed. To do this,
          specify the `--enable-openmp' option when running `configure'
          for FFTW3.

        - _Location of the FFTW3 headers_: In order for GGADT to find
          the Fortran headers for FFTW3, they must be in the standard
          location (`/usr/local/include' or `usr/include') or in
          `$prefix/include' where `$prefix' is defined by doing
          `./configure --prefix=<prefix>' at the configuration step for
          `ggadt'.


   * *Suitable C and Fortran compilers*: GGADT was developed using the
     GNU compiler suite (version 4.9) throughout, but the `configure'
     script will try to work with most common compilers. _Your Fortran
     compiler must be able to compile Fortran 2003 code_.

        - *OpenMP*: _Further requirements for installing
          `ggadt-openmp'_: For the OpenMP version of GGADT, you must
          have C and Fortran compilers that are compatible with OpenMP
          version 4.0. This version of GGADT was tested with the GNU C
          and Fortran compilers (`gcc', `gfortran') version 4.9.


   * *Mac users*
        - Install the latest edition of *XCode command-line tools*. As
          of Mac OSX v10.9.1, the command-line tools are not included
          in XCode automatically, so you have to do this on your own.

        - *Warning* about the "`gcc'" compiler included in the XCode
          command line tools. As I understand it, this is actually a
          front-end to a `clang' compiler, and will cause problems if
          you try to compile `ggadt-openmp'. The `gcc' version is also
          quite dated and might cause other problems. Your best bet is
          to either use another compiler (try the Intel compiler suite)
          or to download later versions of the GNU compilers. We
          recommend obtaining later versions of GNU compilers, which
          you can find here: `http://hpc.sourceforge.net/'.

        - *MacPorts* - In order to avoid confusing the configuration
          script, we recommend you avoid using MacPorts, as they have
          their own directory structure and program names. It might
          still be possible to work with MacPorts as long as all of the
          MacPort program installations that you would need (i.e.
          `gcc', `gfortran') have symlinks to the locations that GNU
          Autoconf expects them to be. I.e., if you have a MacPort
          installation of `gcc' called `gcc-4.8' in some local
          directory, you should have a symlink to the binary `gcc-4.8'
          file in `/usr/bin', with a symlink name of `gcc'. We haven't
          tried this, and thus we offer no gaurantee that this would
          work.

   * (_Optional_) *Python 2.7* or later for some of the included
     scripts.

   * (_Optional_ *matplotlib* python library if you wish to use the
     included plotting scripts.


