3 Invoking GGADT
****************

To see usage and all available options for `ggadt', simply use the `h'
option:

     ggadt -h

3.1 Setting parameter values
============================

The format for running the `ggadt' program (either `ggadt-serial' or
`ggadt-omp') is:

     ggadt OPTION ...

   With no options, `ggadt' runs calculations on a set of default grain
parameters. Parameters may be specified as command-line arguments,

     ggadt --parameter=value ...

   or in a parameter file that is specified as a command-line argument,

     ggadt --parameter-file-name=/path/to/parameterfile

   or a combination of the two:

     ggadt --parameter-file-name=/path/to/parametefile --parameter=value ...

   If a parameter is set by a command-line argument _and_ by a
parameter file, the command-line argument is used.

3.2 Parameter file syntax
=========================

The syntax of parameter files is:

     #comment
     parameter=value
     another-parameter=another-value
     ...

3.3 Options and parameters
==========================

`ggadt' supports the following options:

`--help'
`-h'
     The `help' screen-prints usage information and available options.

`--version'
`-v'
     Print the version number of GGADT on standard output and then exit
     successfully.

`--parameter-file-name=VALUE'
     Path to a correctly formatted parameter file.

`--grain-geometry=VALUE'
     Geometry of dust grain. Must be one of `SPHERE', `ELLIPSOID',
     `SPHERES'. A `SPHERES' grain geometry means that your grain is a
     conglomerate of smaller spheres. If you wish to use this grain
     geometry, you should supply a file (hereafter called a "_cluster
     file_", see the next option) that defines the relative positions
     of the spheres that make up the grain. The sizes of these spheres
     will be normalized so that the effective radius of the grain is
     consistent with `aeff'.

`--cluster-file-name=VALUE'
     Path to a correctly formatted cluster file. Several cluster files
     are included with the distribution, and if you wish to create your
     own, you must mimic exactly the format of these files.

`--aeff=VALUE'
     Effective radius of dust grain. The effective radius is defined to
     be the radius of a sphere with the same volume as the dust grain.

`--ephot=VALUE'
     Energy of the incident X-ray photons in keV.

`--RE-index-of-refraction=VALUE'
     The real component of the complex index of refraction, minus one.

`--IM-index-of-refraction=VALUE'
     The imaginary component of the complex index of refraction.

`--grid-width=VALUE'
     The width of the 2D numerical grid on which projected images of
     the dust grain are resolved, in units of the effective radius of
     the grain. Higher values (>2) give you more angular resolution
     when calculating the differential scattering cross-section, at the
     cost of reducing the resolution of the dust grain on the grid.

`--ngrid=VALUE'
     The number of grid points along one direction of the 2D numerical
     grid on which _images of the grain_ are defined. See above for how
     to use this value together with `grid-width' to give you the
     physical accuracy you desire.

`--nangle=VALUE'
     The number of grain orientations relative to the incoming X-ray
     photon over which to average the differential cross-section.

`--fftw-optimization=VALUE'
     Must be one of `ESTIMATE', `MEASURE', `PATIENT' or `EXHAUSTIVE'.
     FFTW wisdom is saved in `$HOME/.ggadt/plans'. For more information
     about what these tags mean and about FFTW wisdom, see
     `http://fftw.org/fftw3_doc/Words-of-Wisdom_002dSaving-Plans.html#Words-of-Wisdom_002dSaving-Plans'.

`--use-experimental-fft'
`-s'
     Currently not operational, but we are experimenting with a few
     alternative methods for more efficiently performing the FFT.



